description:
lora_l2.c:198-214 panics when lora_recv() returns more bytes than the buffer size:

```c
if (ret > (int)sizeof(rx_buf)) {
    LOG_ERR("CRITICAL: lora_recv returned %d > buffer size %zu - "
            "stack corruption likely, aborting", ret, sizeof(rx_buf));
    k_panic();
}
```

The preceding comment (lines 199-208) explains the reasoning: rx_buf is stack-allocated, so if the driver wrote beyond it, corruption has ALREADY happened. Continuing would risk exploiting corrupted return addresses or saved registers.

What goes right: This is the correct response to detected stack corruption. The log message is actionable - it identifies the specific driver bug. The comment explains why k_panic() is appropriate rather than return/ignore.

Worth defending: Returning an error here would be wrong - it would continue executing on a corrupted stack. Recovery is impossible; restart is the only safe option.
